{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aa907201-6764-4d80-87d0-7ae75d6a2385","content":"In .NET MAUI, `Application` still supports `OnStart`/`OnSleep`/`OnResume`, but the recommended approach is to use **`Window` lifecycle events** instead.\n\nOverride `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and hook into `Window` events, or subclass `Window`:\n\n```csharp\npublic class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        var window = new Window(new MainPage());\n\n        window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnStart  */ };\n        window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnSleep  */ };\n        window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnResume */ };\n\n        return window;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key mappings:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window Event |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart` | `Created` / `Activated` |\n| `OnSleep` | `Stopped` / `Deactivated` |\n| `OnResume` | `Resumed` |\n\nThe `Window` approach is preferred because MAUI supports **multi-window** apps — each window has its own lifecycle. You can also use platform-specific lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` for finer control.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b6406afd-8df7-4546-a892-5c09997d36ca","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle events from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent approach uses the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`. Specifically:\n\n- The `Application` class still exists, but the recommended approach is to use **Window lifecycle events** by overriding `CreateWindow` and subscribing to events, or by using platform-specific lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`.\n\n\n- While `Application` still supports `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume`, the preferred pattern has shifted to `Window` events like `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, and `Resumed`, which map more directly to the old lifecycle methods. You can also override these methods directly on the `Window` class itself.","outputTokens":679,"requestId":"F3C3:22D6D7:1DE1B13:21B49EC:69E81A4F"},"id":"58dd53bd-b40b-46a0-bc22-16f06d18c751","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:46:20.176Z","parentId":"dc29f5d7-078b-4347-9ee9-c27a445d0989"}
